<div id="review_2912977319" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2912977319" />
    <a title="Owlseyes " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6132231-owlseyes"><img alt="Owlseyes " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1626884410p2/6132231.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2912977319?book_show_action=true">Jul 27, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Owlseyes " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Owlseyes " href="/user/show/6132231-owlseyes">Owlseyes </a>
      </span>

          is currently reading it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9788500007958" href="/book/show/2234082.Quando_Nietzsche_Chorou">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6132231-owlseyes?shelf=constructed-nietzsche">constructed-nietzsche</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6132231-owlseyes?shelf=constructed-breuer">constructed-breuer</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2912977319" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1795515129210893286"><a href='https://imgur.com/kKCgCro' rel='nofollow noopener'>
  <img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1564238913i/27895497._SY540_.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/>
</a><br/>(Nietzsche&apos;s sister Elisabeth)<br/><a href='https://imgur.com/1QtgXtx' rel='nofollow noopener'>
  <img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1564238913i/27895496._SY540_.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/>
</a><br/>(Nietzsche and mother)<br/><a href='https://imgur.com/ynanSuR' rel='nofollow noopener'>
  <img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1564238913i/27895498._SX540_.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/>
</a><br/>(Nietzsche, Paul Ree and Lou-Salome, holding the whip)<br/><br/>Lucky me, as I&apos;m reading also &quot;Thus spoke Zarathustra&quot;. Otherwise, Yalom would have me believing something else. Likely. Fiction has its dangers.<br/><br/>Thus far it pictures in my mind this: Yalom had to prove a point, I guess. He had to prove the relevance of existential psychotherapy. His*. So he constructed this character called Breuer, in need of psychotherapy. Moreover, he construct</span>
  <span id="freeText1795515129210893286" style="display:none"><a href="https://imgur.com/kKCgCro" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1564238913i/27895497._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br>(Nietzsche's sister Elisabeth)<br><a href="https://imgur.com/1QtgXtx" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1564238913i/27895496._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br>(Nietzsche and mother)<br><a href="https://imgur.com/ynanSuR" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1564238913i/27895498._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br>(Nietzsche, Paul Ree and Lou-Salome, holding the whip)<br><br>Lucky me, as I'm reading also "Thus spoke Zarathustra". Otherwise, Yalom would have me believing something else. Likely. Fiction has its dangers.<br><br>Thus far it pictures in my mind this: Yalom had to prove a point, I guess. He had to prove the relevance of existential psychotherapy. His*. So he constructed this character called Breuer, in need of psychotherapy. Moreover, he constructed this character called Nietzsche, who, apparently being a loner and sick man [medically speaking] needed psychotherapy, as well. So Nietzsche and Breuer meet, and both become therapists and patients. (True, they swap roles!). Thus: who's the main protagonist? -Existential psychotherapy, the one Yalom is author and main proponent in our days. It's so good a psycho-therapeutic method that made Nietzsche to weep, when having a moment of realization. <br><br>In reality, Breuer and Nietzsche never met in real life. I pretty much doubt that Nietzsche was afflicted by the "despair" Yalom wants us to believe in. HOW COME A MAN WHO MADE THE ANNUNCIATION OF THE OVER-MAN, BE IN EXISTENTIAL ANGST?<br><br>How can one, who thinks of himself as being "dynamite", be in despair? One, who has full confidence in his spirit? A free spirit, as I recently read on his life: "Das Leben eines Freien Geistes".<br><br>And yet Nietzsche had one fear (as he revealed in "Ecce Homo"): that he would be turned into a "saint", in a future time. <br><br>He'd rather be a "clown". <br><br>*<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.amazon.com/Existential-Psychotherapy-Irvin-D-Yalom/dp/0465021476">https://www.amazon.com/Existential-Ps...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="1795515129210893286" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


