    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3274297271" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3274297271" />
    <a title="Philippe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4903281-philippe"><img alt="Philippe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1422300629p2/4903281.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3274297271?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Philippe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Philippe" href="/user/show/4903281-philippe">Philippe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4903281-philippe?shelf=biography">biography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4903281-philippe?shelf=nietzsche">nietzsche</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4903281-philippe?shelf=personal-development">personal-development</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4903281-philippe?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4903281-philippe?shelf=1860-1918">1860-1918</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3274297271" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1814683600397544489">I approached this book with considerable doubt. For decades, Nietzsche has been a mentor to me and the tenor of his life and works have deeply impregnated my worldview. So, one is bound to be disappointed by novelistic impersonations of this complex and demanding human being, thinker, poet. Particularly when its title already suggests emotional entanglements and melodrama. My initial impressions seemed to validate these expectations. The first few chapters struck me as rather cartoonish and I wa</span>
  <span id="freeText1814683600397544489" style="display:none">I approached this book with considerable doubt. For decades, Nietzsche has been a mentor to me and the tenor of his life and works have deeply impregnated my worldview. So, one is bound to be disappointed by novelistic impersonations of this complex and demanding human being, thinker, poet. Particularly when its title already suggests emotional entanglements and melodrama. My initial impressions seemed to validate these expectations. The first few chapters struck me as rather cartoonish and I was ready to put the book aside. But once Lou Salomé disappears from the scene and the interaction between the two protagonists gets going, I became very involved in the story. Yalom did a wonderful job in painting a sober, but to my mind truthful portrait of Nietzsche. It has just the right texture, an intriguing mix of intellectual acuity and spiritual magnanimity. His counterpart, a Jewish medical doctor Josef Breuer, is no less compelling. The book reads like a transcript of a series of 'existential psychotherapy' sessions in which foundational concerns about mortality, purpose, freedom and relationships with other human beings are played out against the background of a rather accurate rendering of Nietzsche's mature philosophy. The story's unity of time and place and its fidelity to quasi-historical circumstances (it's history that <i>might</i> have happened) heighten the reading pleasure. And, yes, Nietzsche's tears were totally justified.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1814683600397544489" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


